Headlines.Headline: The Morning Ledger: Sequester Steams Ahead

PARAGRAPH.#text: It looks like there's no stopping the sequester. The White House and congressional Republicans are poised to let the March 1 deadline pass, with each side betting they'll come out on top in the court of public opinion, the WSJ reports. There'll be some last-minute legislative jockeying today. The Senate is expected to vote on two measures — one from Democrats and the other from Republicans — that would give the government options to avert the cuts. But both are expected to fail, the Hill says. And tomorrow President Obama and congressional leaders will have their first face-to-face meeting on the issue. But no one expects that to produce a breakthrough, either.

Headlines.Headline: Water Policy For NY Power Plants Draws Reliability Concerns

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Mark Peters Of DOW JONES NEWSWIRES NEW YORK (Dow Jones)--Authorities in charge of the reliability of New York State's power supply warn a policy to protect aquatic life could threaten the dependability of electricity supplies and increase air pollution. The New York Independent System Operator, which oversees the grid, and the New York State Public Service Commission are encouraging state regulators to proceed cautiously as they finalize new water-use guidelines for power plants. The proposed policy, first released by the state's environmental regulator in March, would phase out a practice by which plants continually draw water from rivers and bays for cooling.
